{
  "doc_id": "51687",
  "text": "However, the occurrence of these opportunistic human pathogens in oysters poses a health risk if the shellfish are consumed raw. Fernandez-Delgado et al. [CITATION_1] found halophilic (growth in saline concentrations from 3 to 8 %) P. mirabilis as prevailing in the bodies of two oyster species in Venezuela and resistant to several tested antibiotics (mainly tetracycline, ampicillin and penicillin, and cefoxitin and cefazolin). Also, Matyar et al. [CITATION_2] isolated several antibiotic-resistant P. vulgaris and P. penneri strains from the intestines of shrimps inhabiting the Iskenderun Bay, Turkey, which was most probably due to the Iskedrun Bay contamination by industrial and domestic wastes, including hospital ones. It is worth noting that Proteus spp. strains were absent from seawater and sediments, although high amounts of fecal coliforms indicated strong fecal contamination of the Bay. Nimrat et al. [CITATION_3] identified Proteus spp. and P. mirabilis among other bacteria detected in spermatophores from black tiger shrimps (Penaeus monodon) collected from the Andaman Sea, Thailand. Cao et al. [CITATION_4] recognized P. penneri as an agent causing red body disease of commercial white shrimps Penaeus vannamei, cultivated in Xiaoshan, Zheijang, China. Interestingly, the mortality of shrimps was successfully inhibited by the predatory activity of Bdellovibrio bacteriovorus against the P. penneri pathogen; thus, the authors propose this bacterial predator as a potential biocontrol agent. P. penneri strain inter alia was also detected on the body surface of the wild blue crab (Callinectes sapidus) in the Akyatan Lagoon (the south of the Mediterranean Sea) [CITATION_5] .",
